This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. Science fiction author Kevin O'Donnell, Jr.,
a Yale graduate who still lives in New Haven, started writing short stories in

00:49.960 --> 00:57.760
the early 70s. After writing nearly 100 short stories, O'Donnell moved on to
writing novels, and so far he's written six. These include Bandersnatch,

00:57.920 --> 01:06.680
Mayflies, War of Omission, and the Journeys of McGill-Feehan series, Caverns,
Reefs, and Lava. O'Donnell spent a good deal of time in Korea before and after

01:06.680 --> 01:15.080
college, and he majored in Chinese studies at college. We asked him if having
lived in the Orient influences his writing. It hit me on a couple of different

01:15.080 --> 01:26.820
levels. One is, this is more true, I think, of Americans who live in Asia than
those who live in Europe or South America. Because in Asia, you're very

01:26.820 --> 01:36.080
conscious of the fact that you're a foreigner. I mean, you're racially
different. You do not have black hair and dark brown eyes. Everywhere you walk,

01:36.280 --> 01:46.340
people look at you, especially in some of the more rural areas of the country,
like Korea, where the last time they saw an American was during the war, 20

01:46.340 --> 01:59.840
years ago, 20 years before I was there. They are unabashed in their curiosity,
and it really encounters the self-consciousness in the American to constantly be

01:59.840 --> 02:12.180
stared at, to have people touching you, to see if you feel the same as a Korean
does. So I think that's affecting my science fiction writing and how a person

02:12.180 --> 02:25.540
feels when he's among aliens. At the same time, Asian languages and cultures are
significantly different from Western cultures in terms of the way they view

02:25.540 --> 02:38.380
almost everything. And although it's not really an alien psychology, it's
sufficiently different that it gives me sort of an insight into how a sentient

02:38.380 --> 02:52.280
being from Rigel or whatever could view things differently, could take a really
far-out perspective on something we just take for granted.

03:11.900 --> 03:19.600
Mayflies Mayflies is O'Donnell's second novel. It's the story of a generation
ship conveying thousands of settlers to a far destination. But the focus is on

03:19.600 --> 03:26.360
the computer that guides the ship. You see, its core is a living human brain.
That is, retain the memories of the time it was in the body of Dr. Gerard

03:26.360 --> 03:35.320
Metaklura. O'Donnell explains the genesis of this concept. Mayflies started out
as, actually

03:35.320 --> 03:50.080
it was a workshop exercise. I was at the time in a workshop here in New Haven.
And we had to do a, oh, I forget, a two-paragraph description of someone. And I

03:50.080 --> 04:04.180
described this character, Metaklura, who took more than the two paragraphs to
describe. He ran on for about a page and all of a sudden he died. And I took it

04:04.180 --> 04:11.860
into the workshop and people said, well, yes, those are nice paragraphs and very
good description. But boy, what have you done here? You know, you've created a

04:11.860 --> 04:20.000
character and then killed them. What a waste. I got angry and said, well, you
know, maybe I've killed them, but it's not a waste. But I can make something of

04:20.000 --> 04:29.800
them. And they said, we dare you. And pretty soon Mayflies was underway with me
trying to prove he could write a book about a protagonist who died on page one.

04:31.100 --> 04:41.740
And have that protagonist a very vital part of the entire story, rather than
just a haunting memory. The only way to do that was, of course, to somehow keep

04:41.740 --> 04:51.500
him alive. And one thing led to another. And the next thing I knew, Metaklura
was a central computer on the good ship Mayflower. On our next show, we'll talk

04:51.500 --> 04:52.720
more with Kevin O'Donnell Jr.

