12:13.700 --> 12:21.460
This is Daryl Lane. And Bill Vernon. Kevin O'Donnell Jr.'s science fiction
novel, War of Omission, was published in 1982. In the book, O'Donnell describes

12:21.460 --> 12:29.560
a violent revolution which takes place in late 20th century America. This
revolution begins in the Northeast. O'Donnell presents the thoughts and actions

12:29.560 --> 12:38.600
of the participants on both sides of the revolution. We asked him what he was
trying to get across in War of Omission. The modern-day recapitulation of the

12:38.600 --> 12:43.260
statement that power corrupts, and absolute power corrupts absolutely.

12:47.080 --> 12:55.640
Sort of, I was trying to say, hey, you know, it's real easy to say that, you
know, the system stinks and we'll wipe it out. But what happens when you do wipe

12:55.640 --> 13:08.580
it out? You know, I think this is where every revolutionary since, you know, the
French in 1787 has screwed up thoroughly. They say, well, you know, the present

13:08.580 --> 13:18.300
system is corrupt and it's bloated and it stinks and let's throw it out and
we'll have paradise. I think that's stupid. I'm not a defender of the system,

13:18.560 --> 13:32.280
but I think the sort of sweeping, burn it down just doesn't work because, you
know, you wind up building on rubble. You don't move into a structure that you

13:32.280 --> 13:43.520
can clean up and straighten out. I mean, you've got ashes. And I think really
those two things were what the book was all about. The science fictional element

13:43.520 --> 13:51.680
in War of Omission is the tisser, a weapon the revolutionaries perfect, which
wipes out all objects in the target area instantaneously. It makes these objects

13:51.680 --> 13:59.740
disappear. Right, but it does something else as well. It wipes out the memory of
the target area from everyone's minds. So if a person's house and family were

13:59.740 --> 14:06.980
deleted by a tisser, neither he nor anyone else would have any memory of them.
Most of the action, especially tisser deletions, takes place in New Haven, the

14:06.980 --> 14:15.540
city where O'Donnell now lives. We asked O'Donnell if he enjoyed writing scenes
in which New Haven gets destroyed. That generated an interesting sidelight. I

14:15.540 --> 14:29.180
was sort of offended by my publisher that they cut some references in there. We
have a building here in town. It's the Knights of Columbus building, and I think

14:29.180 --> 14:43.240
it's possibly the ugliest structure ever erected anywhere in America. It's a
huge, towering, ugly brick building with massive

14:43.240 --> 14:57.940
turrets at each of the four corners of the building. I mean, it looks like it
was designed to hold off an attack by, you know, maddened archers. And I took

14:57.940 --> 15:06.500
great pleasure in destroying that in the book, having it totally obliterated
from the face of the earth. And at one point I had a character bring it back and

15:06.500 --> 15:08.100
change his mind. It was so ugly.

15:18.140 --> 15:26.440
The concept of the tisser is the heart of War of Omission. O'Donnell told us he
put a lot of effort to make the tisser believable. Well, the hardest part was

15:26.440 --> 15:39.620
trying to make it plausible. And a review or two has appeared that, you know,
has really faulted the book on those grounds. But, you know, for whatever

15:39.620 --> 15:51.820
reason, that person just did not believe the tisser. And I put so much effort
into trying to make it believable. I think I put more effort into that than any

15:51.820 --> 16:02.740
other part of the book, trying to make it seem very natural and trying to
provide possible explanations for why this happened. Sort of brief meditations

16:02.740 --> 16:16.340
on the nature of reality. For those who accepted the explanation, who believed
the tisser, I think the book worked. And I think if you can't believe it, the

16:16.340 --> 16:25.220
book just falls flat. The tisser is believable, and War of Omission works. We'll
look at Kevin O'Donnell Jr.'s Journeys of McGill-Feehan series on our next show.

