This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. Science Fiction author Kevin O'Donnell Jr.
has written many short stories, plus six novels to date. Three of his novels

18:09.700 --> 18:18.660
form a series. The series is called The Journeys of McGill-Feehan, and the three
installments are subtitled Caverns, Reefs, and Lava. McGill-Feehan is a 21st

18:18.660 --> 18:26.760
century earthling who, at age four days, is swallowed by a mysterious, giant,
amoeba-like gastropod, which was sent by the even more mysterious, far-being,

18:27.280 --> 18:36.220
Retz-Glaran. The infant McGill remains in the gastropod precisely 71 hours and
24 minutes. Then he is discharged, and the gastropod leaves the earth with no

18:36.220 --> 18:45.400
comment. McGill seems to be a normal lad. At age five, however, it is discovered
that he has the flinger talent, the extremely rare ability to transmit people or

18:45.400 --> 18:54.220
objects instantaneously to distant destinations in the galaxy, providing the
total mass of any load doesn't exceed 918 kilograms. Young McGill is enrolled in

18:54.220 --> 19:02.140
the Flinger Academy, where he masters the art under the tutelage of experienced
flingers. Then at age 17, he is certified as a flinger. But since McGill is

19:02.140 --> 19:10.480
puzzled about the motive of the far-being for having the gastropod swallow him
for three days, he vows to seek out the far-being and ask him why. Another group

19:10.480 --> 19:17.960
is interested in McGill, too, the organization. They reason that if the far
-being has something in store for McGill, then they want it, too. The stage is

19:17.960 --> 19:25.920
set. Young McGill is mastering flinging while simultaneously learning about such
things in life as romance, trying to live with the flinger bureaucracy, and

19:25.920 --> 19:34.220
searching for the far-being, all the while the sinister organization is after
him. The series is obviously humorous, but it's serious as well. Here O'Donnell

19:34.220 --> 19:50.320
comments on his intention for the series. Well, my primary intent in the McGill
fan series is to do something light, fast-paced, adventuresome, that nonetheless

19:50.320 --> 19:53.400
shows

19:53.400 --> 19:59.140
a person of incredible talent growing up and the problems he faces.

20:02.120 --> 20:16.080
It's that aspect of it tends to take lower priority. I think the adventures of
McGill fan come first. I do want a book that people can sit down and read

20:16.080 --> 20:31.060
quickly and really enjoy. And it's not a gloomy book. Bandersnatch and War of
Omission are sort of downbeat books. Nathlons is, in a way, upbeat, but it's got

20:31.060 --> 20:45.540
a lot of depressing stuff in it. Whereas McGill fan is, it's not. I do it partly
as a change of pace to write a book that just moves right along from the start

20:45.540 --> 20:48.540
to finish and has a lot of things happening.

20:51.920 --> 20:57.280
In the first

20:57.280 --> 21:06.940
book, Caverns, McGill takes charge of a Rangan egg which hatches in book two,
Reefs. He names the young reptilian Rangan Sam, and Sam becomes McGill's

21:06.940 --> 21:17.620
sidekick. Here O'Donnell comments on Sam's role. Poor Sam. I mean, he's going to
grow up so mixed up because he's being raised entirely on Earth. Well, except

21:17.620 --> 21:28.700
for their excursions off world, but he's being raised by a human being, very
human values. But Sam is not human. When he gets to maturity, he's going to be,

21:28.760 --> 21:39.140
oh heavens, from the tip of his nose to the tip of his tail, he's going to be
about 15 feet long, and he's going to stand about, oh, what, four and a half

21:39.140 --> 21:49.000
feet high at the shoulder? The back part of him, and his head will be, you know,
pretty much about six feet off the ground. I mean, he's going to be big. He's

21:49.000 --> 22:02.120
going to be very alien-looking, and he's going to have a lot of trouble because
he's neither one nor the other. He's not a Rangan. He knows nothing of Rangan

22:02.120 --> 22:16.320
culture. But he is not and can never be a human being. I see lots of interesting
problems ahead for Sam. More on Kevin O'Donnell Jr.'s The Journeys of McGill

