This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. Kevin O'Donnell Jr.'s science fiction
series, The Journeys of McGill Feehan, is a highly popular adventure yarn

24:00.560 --> 24:07.420
featuring the young flinger, McGill Feehan, who, after having developed his
talent, is searching for the far being. Not only must young Feehan cope with his

24:07.420 --> 24:15.060
talent, and life in general, he must avoid being captured by the organization.
The series is humorous, but interspersed among the action and humor are the

24:15.060 --> 24:22.680
violent deaths of many of McGill's allies and friends, including his parents,
his lovers, and his roommates. We asked O'Donnell why he so freely dispatches

24:22.680 --> 24:35.060
with most of McGill's acquaintances. Part of that is cold calculation on my
part, that when you're writing a series, one of the real difficulties is

24:35.060 --> 24:42.120
convincing the reader that your hero is in danger. When you write one book,
there's no problem, because the reader doesn't know how it's going to come out.

24:42.300 --> 24:49.840
But when you have a series, the reader says, Well, hey, look, you know, he's
been through 18 of these adventures now, and he's emerged unscathed from every

24:49.840 --> 25:00.320
one, so why worry? And, you know, the reader's emotional involvement in the
story is lessened. But when there is a real danger, when people near and dear to

25:00.320 --> 25:12.060
him are dying, and in some cases dying horribly, it brings the threat much
closer. It makes it much more plausible. And at this point, McGill has lost a

25:12.060 --> 25:24.080
lot of people who are very close to him. His parents, Nadia and Graystein, he's
going to lose more. And, you know, as I say, part of it is cold calculation, but

25:24.080 --> 25:38.940
part of it is also realistic appraisal of the situation fans in. He's got this
talent, he's got this mysterious link with this even more mysterious alien

25:38.940 --> 25:41.680
being, and he has people hot on his trail.

25:44.520 --> 25:55.840
And it streams, you know, readers' credibility to have not only Finn, but all
his friends coming through safe and sound every time. You know, the

25:55.840 --> 26:06.740
organization, they may not be perfect, but they're not total amateurs, and
they're going to be striking real close to home. And they have so far in the

26:06.740 --> 26:15.760
first three books, and they'll continue to. McGill encounters several types of
aliens on his journeys. We ask O'Donnell for what purpose does he use alien

26:15.760 --> 26:22.760
characters in the series. In the fan series, I'm trying to make aliens who are
comprehensible,

26:24.980 --> 26:36.500
and yet who are not human. I really think when we run into alien species, and
sooner or later we will, they will have traits which we recognize as traits that

26:36.500 --> 26:54.280
we have. Now, in Lava, I've got these religious fanatics running around. I
suspect that any sentient race we encounter will, at least in one stage of their

26:54.280 --> 27:03.240
development, have gone through an intensely religious period. It might still be
religious today, if you can tell, that I think any sentient being has to wonder

27:03.240 --> 27:18.060
on its origin, how it came to be, why it came to be, who created the universe.
So, you know, I'm trying to, not to mirror humanity,

27:20.540 --> 27:30.840
but to suggest that there are alternates with which we can have traits,
attitudes in common. So far, O'Donnell has written three books in the McGill

27:30.840 --> 27:43.340
-Feehan series. Here's what O'Donnell said when we asked him if there would be
any more in the series. Yes, definitely. At the moment, it's a McGill story, and

27:43.340 --> 27:58.800
it's from his childhood, it's been published in Berkeley Showcase. There will be
more Feehan books. At the moment, I'm saying seven more, and the series will

27:58.800 --> 28:09.800
end. So, I'm glad to at least ten. Kevin O'Donnell Jr. will keep us entertained
with the adventures of McGill-Feehan for at least a while longer.

